        Considered one of the greatest artists of the Northern Renaissance, Bosch is known for creating restlessly imaginative works rich in religious symbolism, allegory, and fantastical elements depicted in bustling scenes across expansive compositions.Apr 29, 2020

        Who owns Hieronymus Bosch paintings?
        Philip II of Spain
        In the late 16th century, Philip II of Spain acquired many of Bosch's paintings; as a result, the Prado Museum in Madrid now owns The Adoration of the Magi, The Garden of Earthly Delights, the tabletop painting of The Seven Deadly Sins and the Four Last Things and The Haywain Triptych.

        How many Hieronymus Bosch paintings are there?
        Bosch signed only seven of his works, and dated even less. As such, there are only 25 remaining paintings that are sure to be his. His style was highly influential, and he was imitated by numerous followers, which produced many forgeries of his works.

        About

        Description

        Hieronymus Bosch was a Dutch/Netherlandish painter from Brabant. He is one of the most notable representatives of the Early Netherlandish painting school. His work, generally oil on oak wood, mainly contains fantastic illustrations of religious concepts and narratives. Wikipedia
        Born: 's-Hertogenbosch, Netherlands
        Died: August 9, 1516, 's-Hertogenbosch, Netherlands
        Periods: Renaissance, Early Netherlandish painting
        Full name: Jheronimus van Aken
        Nationality: Dutch
        Influenced: Pieter Bruegel the Elder, Salvador Dal, Joan Mir, MORE
